<NotesLayout
  title="Insurance — cover types & questions"
  description="The main protection products, what each is for, and what to ask before buying."
  tag="Insurance"
  updated="28 Jun 2026"
>
  <p>
    Insurance is buying certainty: I pay a known small cost to avoid an unknown
    large one. The question is never "is it worth it on average" — on average the
    insurer wins — but "could I absorb this loss myself?" If not, insure it.
  </p>

  <h2>Main cover types</h2>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Cover</th><th>Protects against</th><th>Pays</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>Life</td><td>Death during the term</td><td>Lump sum (or income) to dependants</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Income protection</td><td>Can't work through illness/injury</td><td>Regular income until recovery/retirement</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Critical illness</td><td>Diagnosis of a listed serious condition</td><td>Lump sum</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Health</td><td>Cost of private treatment</td><td>Treatment costs</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Key person</td><td>Loss of a vital employee/owner</td><td>Lump sum to the business</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h2>How to size it</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Life:</strong> enough to clear debts (mortgage) and replace lost income for as long as dependants need it.</li>
    <li><strong>Income protection:</strong> usually a percentage of gross income; check the <em>deferred period</em> (how long before it pays).</li>
    <li><strong>Term vs whole-of-life:</strong> term is cheaper and covers a defined need; whole-of-life is for a permanent need (e.g. estate planning).</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Questions before buying</h2>
  <blockquote>
    What exactly triggers a payout, and what's excluded? · What's the deferred /
    waiting period? · Are premiums guaranteed or reviewable? · Does it pay once
    (lump sum) or until I recover (income)? · Is the policy written in trust so it
    pays out cleanly?
  </blockquote>

  <hr />
  <p><strong>Rule of thumb:</strong> insure the catastrophic and the unaffordable; self-insure the small and the routine.</p>
</NotesLayout>
